# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: knx-building
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:knx-building/building-automation] BAS functionality may keep a building's climate within a specified range, provide light to rooms based on occupancy, monitor performance and device failures, and provide malfunction alarms to building maintenance staff.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] A BAS works to reduce building energy and maintenance costs compared to a non-controlled building.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Most commercial, institutional, and industrial buildings built after 2000 include a BAS, whilst older buildings may be retrofitted with a new BAS.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] A building controlled by a BAS is often referred to as an "intelligent building", a "smart building", or (if a residence) a *smart home*.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Commercial and industrial buildings have historically relied on robust proven protocols (like BACnet) while proprietary protocols (like X-10) were used in homes.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] With the advent of wireless sensor networks and the Internet of Things, an increasing number of smart buildings are resorting to using low-power wireless communication technologies such as Zigbee, Bluetooth Low Energy and LoRa to interconnect the local sensors, actuators and processing devices.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Almost all multi-story green buildings are designed to accommodate a BAS for the energy, air and water conservation characteristics.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Electrical device demand response is a typical function of a BAS, as is the more sophisticated ventilation and humidity monitoring required of "tight" insulated buildings.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Most green buildings also use as many low-power DC devices as possible.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Even a passivhaus design intended to consume no net energy whatsoever will typically require a BAS to manage heat capture, shading and venting, and scheduling device use.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Building management systems are most commonly implemented in large projects with extensive mechanical, HVAC, and electrical systems.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Systems linked to a BMS typically represent 40% of a building's energy usage; if lighting is included, this number approaches to 70%.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] BMS systems are a critical component to managing energy demand.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Improperly configured BMS systems are believed to account for 20% of building energy usage, or approximately 8% of total energy usage in the United States.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] In addition to controlling the building's internal environment, BMS systems are sometimes linked to access control (turnstiles and access doors controlling who is allowed access and egress to the building) or other security systems such as closed-circuit television (CCTV) and motion detectors.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Fire alarm systems and elevators are also sometimes linked to a BMS for monitoring.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] In case a fire is detected then only the fire alarm panel could close dampers in the ventilation system to stop smoke spreading, shut down air handlers, start smoke evacuation fans, and send all the elevators to the ground floor and park them to prevent people from using them.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Building management systems have also included disaster-response mechanisms (such as base isolation) to save structures from earthquakes.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] In more recent times, companies and governments have been working to find similar solutions for flood zones and coastal areas at-risk to rising sea levels.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Self-adjusting floating environment draws from existing technologies used to float concrete bridges and runways such as Washington's SR 520 and Japan's Mega-Float.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Analog inputs are used to read a variable measurement.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Examples are temperature, humidity and pressure sensors which could be thermistor, 4–20 mA, 0–10 volt or platinum resistance thermometer (resistance temperature detector), or wireless sensors.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] A digital input indicates a device is on or off.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Some examples of digital inputs would be a door contact switch, a current switch, an air flow switch, or a voltage-free relay contact (dry contact).
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Digital inputs could also be pulse inputs counting the pulses over a period of time.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] An example is a turbine flow meter transmitting flow data as a frequency of pulses to an input.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Nonintrusive load monitoring is software relying on digital sensors and algorithms to discover appliance or other loads from electrical or magnetic characteristics of the circuit.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] It is however detecting the event by an analog means.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] These are extremely cost-effective in operation and useful not only for identification but to detect start-up transients, line or equipment faults, etc.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Occupancy sensors detect the presence, number, and sometimes location of people in a space to enable demand-controlled systems for lighting, HVAC, and energy management.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Traditional examples include passive infrared (PIR), ultrasonic, and CO2-based detectors, but advanced systems use low-resolution thermal imaging or area sensors to provide zone-level accuracy without capturing identifiable images, ensuring privacy compliance (e.g., GDPR).
[src:knx-building/building-automation] These sensors output analog heat signatures or digital counts that integrate with building management systems via protocols like BACnet or wireless IoT networks, reducing energy use by up to 40% through precise ventilation and lighting control.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Analog outputs control the speed or position of a device, such as a variable frequency drive, an I-P (current to pneumatics) transducer, or a valve or damper actuator.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] An example is a hot water valve opening up 25% to maintain a setpoint.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Another example is a variable frequency drive ramping up a motor slowly to avoid a hard start.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Digital outputs are used to open and close relays and switches as well as drive a load upon command.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] An example would be to turn on the parking lot lights when a photocell indicates it is dark outside.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Another example would be to open a valve by allowing 24VDC/AC to pass through the output powering the valve.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Analog outputs could also be pulse type outputs emitting a frequency of pulses over a given period of time.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] An example is an energy meter calculating kWh and emitting a frequency of pulses accordingly.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Controllers are essentially small, purpose-built computers with input and output capabilities.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] These controllers come in a range of sizes and capabilities to control devices commonly found in buildings, and to control sub-networks of controllers.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Inputs allow a controller to read temperature, humidity, pressure, current flow, air flow, and other essential factors.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] The outputs allow the controller to send command and control signals to slave devices, and to other parts of the system.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Inputs and outputs can be either digital or analog.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Digital outputs are also sometimes called discrete depending on manufacturer.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Controllers used for building automation can be grouped in three categories: programmable logic controllers (PLCs), system/network controllers, and terminal unit controllers.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] However an additional device can also exist in order to integrate third-party systems (e.g. a stand-alone AC system) into a central building automation system.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Terminal unit controllers usually are suited for control of lighting and/or simpler devices such as a package rooftop unit, heat pump, VAV box, fan coil, etc.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] The installer typically selects one of the available pre-programmed personalities best suited to the device to be controlled, and does not have to create new control logic.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Occupancy is one of two or more operating modes for a building automation system; unoccupied, morning warmup, and night-time setback are other common modes.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Occupancy is usually based on time of day schedules.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] In occupancy mode, the BAS aims to provides a comfortable climate and adequate lighting, often with zone-based control so that users on one side of a building have a different thermostat (or a different system, or sub system) than users on the opposite side.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] A temperature sensor in the zone provides feedback to the controller, so it can deliver heating or cooling as needed.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] If enabled, morning warmup (MWU) mode occurs prior to occupancy.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] During morning warmup the BAS tries to bring the building to setpoint just in time for occupancy.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] The BAS often factors in outdoor conditions and historical experience to optimize MWU.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] This is also referred to as *optimized start*.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Some buildings rely on occupancy sensors to activate lighting or climate conditioning.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Given the potential for long lead times before a space becomes sufficiently cool or warm, climate conditioning is not often initiated directly by an occupancy sensor.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Lighting can be turned on, off, or dimmed with a building automation or lighting control system based on time of day, or on occupancy sensor, photosensors and timers.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] One typical example is to turn the lights in a space on for a half-hour since the last motion was sensed.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] A photocell placed outside a building can sense darkness, and the time of day, and modulate lights in outer offices and the parking lot.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Lighting is also a good candidate for demand response, with many control systems providing the ability to dim (or turn off) lights to take advantage of DR incentives and savings.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] In newer buildings, the lighting control can be based on the field bus Digital Addressable Lighting Interface (DALI).
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Lamps with DALI ballasts are fully dimmable.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] DALI can also detect lamp and ballast failures on DALI luminaires and signals failures.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Shading and glazing are essential components in the building system, they affect occupants' visual, acoustical, and thermal comfort and provide the occupant with a view outdoor.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Automated shading and glazing systems are solutions for controlling solar heat gains and glare.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] It refers to the use of technology to control external or internal shading devices (such as blinds, and shades) or glazing itself.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] The system has an active and rapid response to various changing outdoor data (such as solar, wind) and to changing interior environment (such as temperature, illuminance, and occupant demands).
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Building shading and glazing systems can contribute to thermal and lighting improvement from both energy conservation and comfort point of view.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Dynamic shading devices allow the control of daylight and solar energy to enter into built environment in relation to outdoor conditions, daylighting demands and solar positions.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] The common products include venetian blinds, roller shades, louvers, and shutters.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] They are mostly installed on the interior side of the glazing system because of the low maintenance cost, but also can be used on the exterior or a combination of both.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Most air handlers mix return and outside air so less temperature/humidity conditioning is needed.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] This can save money by using less chilled or heated water (not all AHUs use chilled or hot water circuits).
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Some external air is needed to keep the building's air healthy.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] To optimize energy efficiency while maintaining healthy indoor air quality (IAQ), demand control (or controlled) ventilation (DCV) adjusts the amount of outside air based on measured levels of occupancy.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Analog or digital temperature sensors may be placed in the space or room, the return and supply air ducts, and sometimes the external air.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Actuators are placed on the hot and chilled water valves, the outside air and return air dampers.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] The supply fan (and return if applicable) is started and stopped based on either time of day, temperatures, building pressures or a combination.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] All modern building automation systems have alarm capabilities.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] It does little good to detect a potentially hazardous or costly situation if no one who can solve the problem is notified.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Notification can be through a computer (email or text message), pager, cellular phone voice call, audible alarm, or all of these.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] For insurance and liability purposes all systems keep logs of who was notified, when and how.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Alarms may immediately notify someone or only notify when alarms build to some threshold of seriousness or urgency.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] At sites with several buildings, momentary power failures can cause hundreds or thousands of alarms from equipment that has shut down – these should be suppressed and recognized as symptoms of a larger failure.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Some sites are programmed so that critical alarms are automatically re-sent at varying intervals.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] For example, a repeating critical alarm (of an uninterruptible power supply in 'bypass') might resound at 10 minutes, 30 minutes, and every 2 to 4 hours thereafter until the alarms are resolved.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Security systems can be interlocked to a building automation system.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] If occupancy sensors are present, they can also be used as burglar alarms.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Because security systems are often deliberately sabotaged, at least some detectors or cameras should have battery backup and wireless connectivity and the ability to trigger alarms when disconnected.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Modern systems typically use power-over-Ethernet (which can operate a pan-tilt-zoom camera and other devices up to 30–90 watts) which is capable of charging such batteries and keeps wireless networks free for genuinely wireless applications, such as backup communication in outage.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Fire alarm panels and their related smoke alarm systems are usually hard-wired to override building automation.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] For example: if the smoke alarm is activated, all the outside air dampers close to prevent air coming into the building, and an exhaust system can isolate the blaze.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Similarly, electrical fault detection systems can turn entire circuits off, regardless of the number of alarms this triggers or persons this distresses.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Fossil fuel combustion devices also tend to have their own over-rides, such as natural gas feed lines that turn off when slow pressure drops are detected (indicating a leak), or when excess methane is detected in the building's air supply.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] ASHRAE's open protocol BACnet or the open protocol LonTalk specify how most such devices interoperate.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Modern systems use SNMP to track events, building on decades of history with SNMP-based protocols in the computer networking world.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Physical connectivity between devices was historically provided by dedicated optical fiber, ethernet, ARCNET, RS-232, RS-485 or a low-bandwidth special purpose wireless network.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Modern systems rely on standards-based multi-protocol heterogeneous networking such as that specified in the IEEE 1905.1 standard and verified by the nVoy auditing mark.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Proprietary hardware dominates the controller market.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Each company has controllers for specific applications.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Some are designed with limited controls and no interoperability, such as simple packaged roof top units for HVAC.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Software will typically not integrate well with packages from other vendors.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Cooperation is at the Zigbee/BACnet/LonTalk level only.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Current systems provide interoperability at the application level, allowing users to mix-and-match devices from different manufacturers, and to provide integration with other compatible building control systems.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] These typically rely on SNMP, long used for this same purpose to integrate diverse computer networking devices into one coherent network.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] With the growing spectrum of capabilities and connections to the Internet of Things, building automation systems were repeatedly reported to be vulnerable, allowing hackers and cybercriminals to attack their components.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Buildings can be exploited by hackers to measure or change their environment: sensors allow surveillance (e.g. monitoring movements of employees or habits of inhabitants) while actuators allow to perform actions in buildings (e.g. opening doors or windows for intruders).
[src:knx-building/building-automation] Several vendors and committees started to improve the security features in their products and standards, including KNX, Zigbee and BACnet (see recent standards or standard drafts).
[src:knx-building/building-automation] However, researchers report several open problems in building automation security.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] On November 11, 2019, a 132-page security research paper was released titled "I Own Your Building (Management System)" by Gjoko Krstic and Sipke Mellema that addressed more than 100 vulnerabilities affecting various BMS and access control solutions by various vendors.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] On November 24, 2025, a 161-page security research paper was released titled "Project Brainfog: Beyond the Facade - Exposing Smart Giants" by Gjoko Krstic that addressed more than 1000 vulnerabilities affecting two widely used BAS controllers by ABB Group.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] It is common for room automation systems to employ a touchscreen as the primary way of controlling each operation.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] On November 27, 2018, a 29-page research paper titled "A Scalable Room Occupancy Prediction with Transferable Time Series Decomposition of CO2 Sensor Data" was published by Irvan Bastian Arief, Margaret Hamilton, and Flora Salim.
[src:knx-building/building-automation] The paper introduced a novel approach to leveraging carbon dioxide (CO2) sensor data to predict room occupancy—enabling smarter building automation by estimating the number of occupants in a room at any given time.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] The phrase **smart home** refers to home automation devices that have internet access.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] Home automation, a broader category, includes *any* device that can be monitored or controlled via wireless radio signals, not just those having internet access.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] When connected with the Internet, home sensors and activation devices are an important constituent of the Internet of Things ("IoT").
[src:knx-building/home-automation] A home automation system typically connects controlled devices to a central smart home hub (sometimes called a "gateway").
[src:knx-building/home-automation] The user interface for control of the system uses either wall-mounted terminals, tablet or desktop computers, a mobile phone application, or a Web interface that may also be accessible off-site through the Internet.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] Early home automation began with labor-saving machines.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] Self-contained electric or gas powered home appliances became viable in the 1900s with the introduction of electric power distribution and led to the introduction of washing machines (1904), water heaters (1889), refrigerators (1913), sewing machines, dishwashers, and clothes dryers.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] In 1975, the first general purpose home automation network technology, X10, was developed.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] It is a communication protocol for electronic devices.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] It primarily uses electric power transmission wiring for signalling and control, where the signals involve brief radio frequency bursts of digital data, and remains the most widely available.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] By 2012, in the United States, according to ABI Research, 1.5 million home automation systems were installed.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] Per research firm Statista more than 45 million smart home devices will be installed in U.S. homes by the end of the year 2018.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] From 2018 to 2023, the number of U.S. homes equipped with smart devices grew at 10.2% per year to reach 63.43 million by 2023.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] The word "*domotics*" is a contraction of the Latin word for a home (*domus*) and the word *robotics*.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] The word "smart" in "smart home" refers to the system being aware of the state of its devices, which is done through the information and communication technologies (ICT) protocol and the Internet of Things (IoT).
[src:knx-building/home-automation] In 2011, Microsoft Research found that home automation could involve a high cost of ownership, inflexibility of interconnected devices, and poor manageability.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] When designing and creating a home automation system, engineers take into account several factors including scalability, how well the devices can be monitored and controlled, ease of installation and use for the consumer, affordability, speed, security, and ability to diagnose issues.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] Findings from iControl showed that consumers prioritize ease-of-use over technical innovation, and although consumers recognize that new connected devices have an unparalleled cool factor, they are not quite ready to use them in their own homes yet.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] Historically, systems have been sold as complete systems where the consumer relies on one vendor for the entire system including the hardware, the communications protocol, the central hub, and the user interface.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] However, there are now open hardware and open source software systems which can be used instead of or with proprietary hardware.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] Many of these systems interface with consumer electronics such as the Arduino or Raspberry Pi, which are easily accessible online and in most electronics stores.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] In addition, home automation devices are increasingly interfaced with mobile phones through Bluetooth, allowing for increased affordability and customizability for the user.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] Customers may hesitate to bet their IoT future on proprietary software or hardware devices that use proprietary protocols that may fade or become difficult to customize and interconnect.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] The nature of home automation devices can also be a problem for security, data security and data privacy, since patches to bugs found in the core operating system often do not reach users of older and lower-price devices.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] One set of researchers say that the failure of vendors to support older devices with patches and updates leaves more than 87% of active devices vulnerable.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] Concerns have been raised by tenants renting from landlords who decide to upgrade units with smart home technology.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] These concerns include weak wireless connections that render the door or appliance unusable or impractical; the security of door passcodes kept by the landlord; and the potential invasion of privacy that comes with connecting smart home technologies to home networks.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] Researchers have also conducted user studies to determine what the barriers are for consumers when integrating home automation devices or systems into their daily lifestyle.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] One of the main takeaways was regarding ease of use, as consumers tend to steer towards "plug and play" solutions over more complicated setups.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] One study found that there were large gaps in the mental-models generated by users regarding how the devices actually work.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] Specifically, the findings showed that there was a lot of misunderstanding related to where the data collected by smart devices was stored and how it was used.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] For example, in a smart light setup, one participant thought that her iPad communicated directly with the light, telling it to either turn-off or on.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] In reality, the iPad sends a signal to the cloud system that the company uses (in this case, the Hue Bridge) which then signals directly to the device.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] Overall, this field is still evolving and the nature of each device is constantly changing.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] While technologists work to create more secure, streamlined, and standardized security protocols, consumers also need to learn more about how these devices work and what the implications of putting them in their homes can be.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] The growth of this field is currently limited not only by technology but also by a user's ability to trust a device and integrate it successfully into his/her daily life.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] Utilizing home automation could lead to more efficient and intelligent energy-saving techniques.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] To do this, researchers propose using data from sensors regarding consumer activity within the home to anticipate consumer needs and balance that with energy consumption.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] Furthermore, home automation has a large potential regarding family safety and security.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] According to a 2015 survey done by iControl, the primary drivers of the demand for smart and connected devices are first "personal and family security", and second "excitement about energy savings".
[src:knx-building/home-automation] Home automation includes a variety of smart security systems and surveillance setups.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] This allows consumers to monitor their homes while away, and to give trusted family members access to that information in case anything bad happens.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] While there are many competing vendors, there are increasing efforts towards open source systems.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] However, there are issues with the current state of home automation including a lack of standardized security measures and deprecation of older devices without backwards compatibility.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] Home automation has high potential for sharing data between family members or trusted individuals for personal security purposes and could lead to energy saving measures with a positive environmental impact in the future.
[src:knx-building/home-automation] The home automation market was worth US$64 billion in 2022 and is projected to grow to over $163 billion in 2028.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] It can use twisted pair (in a tree, line or star topology), powerline, RF, or IP links.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] On this network, the devices form distributed applications and tight interaction is possible.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] This is implemented via interworking models with standardised datapoint types and objects, modelling logical device channels.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] The KNX standard has been built on the OSI-based EIB communication stack extended with the physical layers, configuration modes and application experience of BatiBUS and EHS.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] KNX is not based on a specific hardware platform and a network can be controlled by anything from an 8-bit microcontroller to a PC, according to the demands of a particular building.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] The most common form of installation is over twisted pair medium.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] It is administered by the KNX Association cvba, a non-profit organisation governed by Belgian law which was formed in 1999.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] The KNX Association had 500 registered hardware and software vendor members from 45 nations as at 1 July 2021.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] It had partnership agreements with 100,000 installer companies in 172 countries and more than 500 registered training centres.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] This is a royalty-free open standard and thus access to the KNX specifications is unrestricted.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] KNX devices are commonly connected by a twisted pair bus and can be modified from a controller.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] Classifying devices as either "sensor" or "actuator" is outdated and simplistic.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] Many actuators include controller functionality, but also sensor functionality (for instance measuring operating hours, number of switch cycles, current, electrical power consumption, and more).
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] Application software, together with system topology and commissioning software, is loaded onto the devices via a system interface component.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] Installed systems can be accessed via LAN, point to point links, or phone networks for central or distributed control of the system via computers, tablets and touch screens, and smartphones.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] Central to the KNX architecture concepts are **datapoints** (inputs, outputs, parameters, and diagnostic data) which represent process and control variables in the system.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] The standardised containers for these datapoints are **group objects** and **interface object properties**.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] The communication system offers a reduced instruction set to read and write datapoint values.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] Datapoints have to conform to standardised **datapoint types**, themselves grouped into **functional blocks**.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] These functional blocks and datapoint types are related to applications fields, but some of them are of general use (such as date and time).
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] Datapoints may be accessed through unicast or multicast mechanisms.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] The common kernel sits on top of the physical layers and the medium-specific data link layer and is shared by all the devices on the KNX Network.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] An installation has to be configured at the network topology level and at individual nodes or devices.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] The first level is a precondition or “bootstrap” phase, prior to the configuration of the distributed applications, i.e. binding and parameter setting.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] Configuration may be achieved through a combination of local activity on the devices (such pushing a button), and active network management communication over the bus (peer-to-peer, or more centralized master-slave).
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] Some modes require more active management over the bus, whereas some others are mainly oriented towards local configuration.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] KNX encompasses tools for project engineering tasks such as linking a series of individual devices into a functioning installation and integrating different media and configuration modes.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] This is embodied in an *Engineering Tool Software* (ETS) suite.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] A KNX installation always consists of a set of devices connected to the bus or network.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] Device models vary according to node roles, capabilities, management features and configuration modes, and are all laid down in the **profiles**.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] There are also general-purpose device models, such as for bus coupling units (BCUs) or bus interface modules (BIMs).
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] Devices may be identified and subsequently accessed throughout the network either by their individual address, or by their unique serial number, depending on the configuration mode.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] (Unique serial numbers are allocated by the KNX Association Certification Department.) Devices can also disclose both a manufacturer specific reference and functional (manufacturer independent) information when queried.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] A KNX wired network can be formed with tree, line and star topologies, which can be mixed as needed; ring topologies are *not* supported.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] A tree topology is recommended for a large installation.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] KNX can link up to 57,375 devices using 16-bit addresses.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] Coupling units allow address filtering which helps to improve performance given the limited bus signal speed.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] An installation based on KNXnet/IP allows the integration of KNX sub networks via IP as the KNX address structure is similar to an IP address.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] The TP1 twisted pair bus (inherited from EIB) provides asynchronous, character oriented data transfer and half-duplex bidirectional differential signaling with a signaling speed of 9600 bit/s.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] Every bus user has equal data transmission rights and data is exchanged directly (peer-to-peer) between bus users.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] SELV power is distributed via the same pair for low-power devices.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] A deprecated specification, TP0, running at a slower signalling speed of 4800 bit/s, has been retained from the BatiBUS standard but KNX products cannot exchange information with BatiBUS devices.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] PL 110 power-line transmission is delivered using spread frequency shift keying signalling with asynchronous transmission of data packets and half duplex bi-directional communication.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] It uses the central frequency 110 kHz (CENELEC B-band) and has a data rate of 1200 bit/s.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] KNX Powerline is aimed at smart white goods, but the take-up has been low.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] An alternative variant, PL 132, has a carrier frequency centred on 132.5 kHz (CENELEC C-band).
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] RF enables communication in the 868.3 MHz band for using frequency shift keying with Manchester data encoding.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] KNXnet/IP port 3671 has integration solutions for IP-enabled media like Ethernet (IEEE 802.2), Bluetooth, WiFi/Wireless LAN (IEEE 802.11), FireWire (IEEE 1394) etc.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] KNX Telegrams can be signed or encrypted thanks to the extension of the protocol that was developed starting in 2013, KNX Data Secure for securing telegrams on the traditional KNX media TP and RF and KNX IP Secure for securing KNX telegrams tunnelled via IP.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] KNX Data Secure became an EN standard (EN 50090-3-4) in 2018, KNX IP Secure an ISO standard (ISO 22510) in 2019.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] Any product labeled with the KNX trademark must be certified to conform with the standards (and thus interoperable with other devices) by accredited third party test labs.
[src:knx-building/knx-standard] All products bearing the KNX logo are programmed through a common interface using the vendor-independent ETS software.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] A **lighting control system** is intelligent network-based lighting control that incorporates communication between various system inputs and outputs related to lighting control with the use of one or more central computing devices.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Lighting control systems are widely used on both indoor and outdoor lighting of commercial, industrial, and residential spaces.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Lighting control systems are sometimes referred to under the term **smart lighting**.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Lighting control systems serve to provide the right amount of light where and when it is needed.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Lighting control systems are employed to maximize the energy savings from the lighting system, satisfy building codes, or comply with green building and energy conservation programs.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Lighting control systems may include a lighting technology designed for energy efficiency, convenience and security.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] This may include high efficiency fixtures and automated controls that make adjustments based on conditions such as occupancy or daylight availability.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Lighting is the deliberate application of light to achieve some aesthetic or practical effect (e.g. illumination of a security breach).
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] It includes task lighting, accent lighting, and general lighting.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] The term *lighting controls* is typically used to indicate stand-alone control of the lighting within a space.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] This may include occupancy sensors, timeclocks, and photocells that are hard-wired to control fixed groups of lights independently.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Adjustment occurs manually at each devices location.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] The efficiency of and market for residential lighting controls has been characterized by the Consortium for Energy Efficiency.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] The term *lighting control system* refers to an intelligent networked system of devices related to lighting control.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] These devices may include relays, occupancy sensors, photocells, light control switches or touchscreens, and signals from other building systems (such as fire alarm or HVAC).
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Adjustment of the system occurs both at device locations and at central computer locations via software programs or other interface devices.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] The major advantage of a lighting control system over stand-alone lighting controls or conventional manual switching is the ability to control individual lights or groups of lights from a single user interface device.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] This ability to control multiple light sources from a user device allows complex lighting scenes to be created.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] A room may have multiple scenes pre-set, each one created for different activities in the room.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] A major benefit of lighting control systems is reduced energy consumption.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Longer lamp life is also gained when dimming and switching off lights when not in use.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Wireless lighting control systems provide additional benefits including reduced installation costs and increased flexibility over where switches and sensors may be placed.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Lighting applications represents 19% of the world's energy use and 6% of all greenhouse emissions.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] In the United States, 65 percent of energy consumption is used by commercial and industrial sectors, and 22 percent of this is used for lighting.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Smart lighting enables households and users to remotely control cooling, heating, lighting and appliances, minimizing unnecessary light and energy use.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] This ability saves energy and provides a level of comfort and convenience.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] From outside the traditional lighting industry, the future success of lighting will require involvement of a number of stakeholders and stakeholder communities.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] The concept of smart lighting also involves utilizing natural light from the sun to reduce the use of man-made lighting, and the simple concept of people turning off lighting when they leave a room.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] A smart lighting system can ensure that dark areas are illuminated when in use.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] The lights actively respond to the activities of the occupants based on sensors and intelligence (logic) that anticipates the lighting needs of an occupant.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] This can enhance comfort, improve safety, reduce manual effort, and improve energy efficiency.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Lights can be used to dissuade those from areas they should not be.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] A security breach, for example, is an event that could trigger floodlights at the breach point.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Preventative measures include illuminating key access points (such as walkways) at night and automatically adjusting the lighting when a household is away to make it appear as though there are occupants.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Chronological time schedules incorporate specific times of the day, week, month or year.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Solar time schedules incorporate sunrise and sunset times, often used to switch outdoor lighting.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Solar time scheduling requires that the location of the building be set.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] This is accomplished using the building's geographic location via either latitude and longitude or by picking the nearest city in a given database giving the approximate location and corresponding solar times.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Space occupancy is primarily determined with occupancy sensors.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Smart lighting that utilizes occupancy sensors can work in unison with other lighting connected to the same network to adjust lighting per various conditions.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] The table below shows potential electricity savings from using occupancy sensors to control lighting in various types of spaces.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] The advantages of ultrasonic devices are that they are sensitive to all types of motion and generally there are zero coverage gaps, since they can detect movements not within the line of sight.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Electric lighting energy use can be adjusted by automatically dimming and/or switching electric lights in response to the level of available daylight.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Reducing the amount of electric lighting used when daylight is available is known as daylight harvesting.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] In response to daylighting technology, daylight-linked automated response systems have been developed to further reduce energy consumption.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] These technologies are helpful, but they do have their downfalls.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Many times, rapid and frequent switching of the lights on and off can occur, particularly during unstable weather conditions or when daylight levels are changing around the switching illuminance.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Not only does this disturb occupants, it can also reduce lamp life.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] A variation of this technology is the 'differential switching' or 'dead-band' photoelectric control which has multiple illuminances it switches from to reduce occupants being disturbed.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Alarm conditions typically include inputs from other building systems such as the fire alarm or HVAC system, which may trigger an emergency 'all lights on' or ' all lights flashing' command for example.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Program logic can tie all of the above elements together using constructs such as if-then-else statements and logical operators.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Digital Addressable Lighting Interface (DALI) is specified in the IEC 62386 standard.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] The use of automatic light dimming is an aspect of smart lighting that serves to reduce energy consumption.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Manual light dimming also has the same effect of reducing energy use.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] A complete sensor consists of a motion detector, an electronic control unit, and a controllable switch/relay.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] The detector senses motion and determines whether there are occupants in the space.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] It also has a timer that signals the electronic control unit after a set period of inactivity.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] The control unit uses this signal to activate the switch/relay to turn equipment on or off.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] For lighting applications, there are three main sensor types: passive infrared, ultrasonic, and hybrid.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Motion-detecting (microwave), heating-sensing (infrared), and sound-sensing; optical cameras, infrared motion, optical trip wires, door contact sensors, thermal cameras, micro radars, daylight sensors.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] In the 1980s there was a strong requirement to make commercial lighting more controllable so that it could become more energy efficient.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Initially this was done with analog control, allowing fluorescent ballasts and dimmers to be controlled from a central source.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] This was a step in the right direction, but cabling was complicated and therefore not cost effective.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Tridonic was an early company to go digital with their broadcast protocols, DSI, in 1991.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] DSI was a basic protocol as it transmitted one control value to change the brightness of all the fixtures attached to the line.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] What made this protocol more attractive, and able to compete with the established analog option, was the simple wiring.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] In production lighting 0-10V system was replaced by analog multiplexed systems such as D54 and AMX192, which themselves have been almost completely replaced by DMX512.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] For dimmable fluorescent lamps (where it operates instead at 1-10 V, where 1 V is minimum and 0 V is off) the system is being replaced by DSI, which itself is in the process of being replaced by DALI.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Those are all wired lighting control systems.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] There are also wireless lighting control systems that are based on some standard protocols like MIDI, ZigBee, Bluetooth Mesh, and others.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] The standard for digital addressable lighting interface, mostly in professional and commercial deployments, is IEC 62386-104.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] This standard specifies the underlying technologies, which in wireless are VEmesh, which operates in the industrial Sub-1 GHz frequency band and Bluetooth Mesh, which operates in the 2.4 GHz frequency band.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] The new type of control for lighting system is using Bluetooth connection directly to the lighting system.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] It is recently introduced by Philips HUE and company new name as Signify formerly known as Philips Lighting.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] This system will need a smartphone or tablet where the user can install a special Philips Hue Bluetooth app.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] The Bluetooth bulbs don't need a Philips Hue bridge to function.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] There is no need to have a Wi-Fi or data connection for controlling the lights with that system.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Smart lighting systems can be controlled using the internet to adjust lighting brightness and schedules.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] One technology involves a smart lighting network that assigns IP addresses to light bulbs.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Schubert predicts that revolutionary lighting systems will provide an entirely new means of sensing and broadcasting information.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] By blinking far too rapidly for any human to notice, the light will pick up data from sensors and carry it from room to room, reporting such information as the location of every person within a high-security building.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] A major focus of the Future Chips Constellation is smart lighting, a revolutionary new field in photonics based on efficient light sources that are fully tunable in terms of such factors as spectral content, emission pattern, polarization, color temperature, and intensity.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Architectural lighting control systems can integrate with a theater's on-off and dimmer controls, and are often used for house lights and stage lighting, and can include worklights, rehearsal lighting, and lobby lighting.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Control stations can be placed in several locations in the building and range in complexity from single buttons that bring up preset options-looks, to in-wall or desktop LCD touchscreen consoles.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Much of the technology is related to residential and commercial lighting control systems.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] The benefit of architectural lighting control systems in the theater is the ability for theater staff to turn worklights and house lights on and off without having to use a lighting control console.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Alternately, the light designer can control these same lights with light cues from the lighting control console so that, for instance, the transition from houselights being up before a show starts and the first light cue of the show is controlled by one system.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] The function of a traditional emergency lighting system is the supply of a minimum illuminating level when a line voltage failure appears.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Therefore, emergency lighting systems have to store energy in a battery module to supply lamps in case of failure.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] In this kind of lighting systems the internal damages, for example battery overcharging, damaged lamps and starting circuit failure must be detected and repaired by specialist workers.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] For this reason, the smart lighting prototype can check its functional state every fourteen days and dump the result into a LED display.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] With these features they can test themselves checking their functional state and displaying their internal damages.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Also the maintenance cost can be decreased.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] The main idea is the substitution of the simple line voltage sensing block that appears in the traditional systems by a more complex one based on a microcontroller.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] This new circuit will assume the functions of line voltage sensing and inverter activation, by one side, and the supervision of all the system: lamp and battery state, battery charging, external communications, correct operation of the power stage, etc., by the other side.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] The system has a great flexibility, for instance, it would be possible the communication of several devices with a master computer, which would know the state of each device all the time.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] A new emergency lighting system based on an intelligent module has been developed.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] The micro-controller as a control and supervision device guarantees increase in the installation security and a maintenance cost saving.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Another important advantage is the cost saving for mass production specially whether a microcontroller with the program in ROM memory is used.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] The advances achieved in photonics are already transforming society just as electronics revolutionized the world in recent decades and it will continue to contribute more in the future.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] From the statistics, North America's optoelectronics market grew to more than $20 billion in 2003.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] The LED (light-emitting diode) market is expected to reach $5 billion in 2007, and the solid-state lighting market is predicted to be $50 billion in 15–20 years, as stated by E.
[src:knx-building/lighting-control-system] Fred Schubert, Wellfleet Senior Distinguished Professor of the Future Chips Constellation at Rensselaer.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] For additional noise immunity, twisted-pair cabling may be shielded.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Cable with shielding is known as **shielded twisted pair** (**STP**) and without as **unshielded twisted pair** (**UTP**).
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] A twisted pair can be used as a balanced line, which as part of a balanced circuit can greatly reduce the effect of noise currents induced on the line by coupling of electric or magnetic fields.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] The idea is that the currents induced in each of the two wires are very nearly equal.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] The twisting ensures that the two wires are on average the same distance from the interfering source and are affected equally.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] The noise thus produces a common-mode signal which can be canceled at the receiver by detecting the difference signal only, the latter being the wanted signal.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Common-mode rejection starts to fail on untwisted wires when the noise source is close to the signal wires; the closer wire will couple with the noise more strongly and the receiver will be unable to eliminate it.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] This problem is especially apparent in telecommunication cables where pairs in the same cable lie next to each other for many miles.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Twisting the pairs counters this effect as on each half twist the wire nearest to the noise source is exchanged.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Provided the interfering source remains uniform, or nearly so, over the distance of a single twist, the induced noise will remain common mode.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] The twist rate (also called *pitch* of the twist, usually defined in twists per meter) makes up part of the specification for a given type of cable.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] When nearby pairs have equal twist rates, the same conductors of the different pairs may repeatedly lie next to each other, partially undoing the benefits of twisting.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] For this reason, it is commonly specified that, at least for cables containing small numbers of pairs, the twist rates must differ.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] In contrast to shielded or foiled twisted pair (typically S/FTP or F/UTP cable shielding), UTP cable is not surrounded by any shielding.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] UTP is the primary wire type for telephone usage and is very common for computer networking.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] The earliest telephones used telegraph lines which were single-wire earth return circuits.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] In the 1880s electric trams were installed in many cities, which induced noise into these circuits.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] In some countries, the tram companies were held responsible for disruption to existing telegraph lines and had to pay for remedial work.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] For new installations, however, it was necessary to protect against existing trams from the outset.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Interference on telephone lines is even more disruptive than it is on telegraph lines.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Telephone companies converted to balanced circuits, which had the incidental benefit of reducing attenuation, hence increasing range.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] As electrical power distribution became more commonplace, this measure proved inadequate.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Two wires, strung on either side of cross bars on utility poles, shared the route with electrical power lines.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Within a few years, the growing use of electricity again brought an increase of interference, so engineers devised a method called wire transposition, to cancel out the interference.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] In wire transposition, the wires exchange position once every several poles.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] In this way, the two wires would receive similar EMI from power lines.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] This represented an early implementation of twisting, with a twist rate of about four twists per kilometer, or six per mile.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Such open-wire balanced lines with periodic transpositions still survive today in some rural areas.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Twisted-pair cabling was invented by Alexander Graham Bell in 1881.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] By 1900, the entire American telephone network was either twisted pair or open wire with transposition to guard against interference.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Today, most of the twisted pairs in the world are outdoor landlines, owned and maintained by telephone companies, used for voice service.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Unshielded twisted pair (UTP) cables are found in many Ethernet networks and telephone systems.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] For indoor telephone applications, UTP is often grouped into sets of 25 pairs according to a standard 25-pair color code originally developed by AT&T.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] A typical subset of these colors (white/blue, blue/white, white/orange, orange/white) shows up in most UTP cables.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] The cables are typically made with copper wires measured at 22 or 24 American Wire Gauge (AWG), with the colored insulation typically made from an insulator such as polyethylene or FEP and the total package covered in a polyethylene jacket.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] For urban outdoor telephone cables containing hundreds or thousands of pairs, the cable is divided into small but identical bundles.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Each bundle consists of twisted pairs that have different twist rates, as pairs having the same twist rate within the cable can still experience some degree of crosstalk.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] The bundles are in turn twisted together to make up the cable.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] UTP is also the most common cable used in computer networking.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Modern Ethernet, the most common data networking standard, can use UTP cables, with increasing data rates requiring higher specification variants of the UTP cable.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Twisted-pair cabling is often used in data networks for short and medium-length connections because of its relatively lower costs compared to optical fiber and coaxial cable.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] As UTP cable bandwidth has improved to match the baseband of television signals, UTP is now used in some video applications, primarily in security cameras.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] As UTP is a balanced transmission line, a balun is needed to connect to unbalanced equipment, for example any using BNC connectors and designed for coaxial cable.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Twisted pair cables may incorporate shielding in an attempt to prevent electromagnetic interference.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Shielding provides an electrically conductive barrier to attenuate electromagnetic waves external to the shield.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] The shield also provides a conduction path by which induced currents can be circulated and returned to the source via a ground reference connection.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Such shielding can be applied to individual pairs or to a collection of pairs.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] When shielding is applied to a collection of pairs, it is usually referred to as screening, but usage among vendors and authors in applying such words as *screening*, *shielding*, and *STP (shielded twisted pair)* can be subject to variability.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Shielded Cat 5e, Cat 6/6A, and Cat 8/8.1 cables typically have F/UTP construction, while shielded Cat 7/7A and Cat 8.2 cables use S/FTP construction.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Because the shielding is conductive, it may also serve as a path to ground.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] A foil-shielded, twisted pair cable may have an integrally incorporated grounding wire called a *drain wire* which makes electrical contact with the shield.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] The purpose of the drain wire is for easy connection to terminals which are usually designed for connection of round wires.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] An early example of shielded twisted-pair was IBM STP-A, which is a two-pair 150 ohm S/FTP cable defined in 1985 by the IBM Cabling System specifications, and used with Token Ring or FDDI networks.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Before digital communication and Ethernet became widespread there was no international standard for telephone cable.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] For instance, in the UK the General Post Office specified CW1293 and CW1308 cables.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] CW1308 was a similar specification to the earlier CW1293 but with an improved color code.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] CW1293 used mostly solid colors on the cores making it difficult to identify the pair it was twisted with without stripping back a large amount of sheath.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] CW1308 has narrow rings of the paired color printed over the base color.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Both cables are a similar standard to category 3 cable.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Cables with categories 3 through 7 have 4 twisted pairs.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Prior to the common use of polyethylene and other plastics for insulation, telephone twisted pair cable was insulated with waxed paper or cotton with a wax coating applied to the copper.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] The overall sheath of this type of cable was usually lead.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] This style of cable came into use in the late 19th century shortly after the invention of the telephone.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] The cable termination in termination boxes were sealed with molten wax or a resin to prevent the ingress of moisture which would seriously degrade the insulating properties of the paper insulation.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] However, such seals made future maintenance and changes more difficult.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] These cables are no longer made but are still occasionally encountered in old buildings and in various external areas, commonly rural villages.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] A loaded twisted pair has intentionally added inductance and was formerly common practice on telecommunication lines.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] The added inductors are known as load coils and reduce attenuation for voiceband frequencies but increase it on higher frequencies.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Load coils reduce distortion in voiceband on very long lines.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] In this context a line without load coils is referred to as an unloaded line.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] A bonded twisted pair is a construction variant in which the two wires of each pair are bonded together for the length of the cable.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Pioneered by Belden, it is intended to help assure configuration consistency during and after installation.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] One key benefit is that the noise immunity performance of the cable can be protected despite potentially rough handling.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] The enhanced performance may be unnecessary and bonding reduces the flexibility of the cable and makes it prone to failure where it is flexed.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] A twisted ribbon cable is a variant of standard ribbon cable in which adjacent pairs of conductors are bonded and twisted together.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] The twisted pairs are then lightly bonded to each other in a ribbon format.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Periodically along the ribbon, there are short sections with no twisting where connectors may be attached using the usual ribbon cable IDC techniques.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] A solid-core cable uses one solid wire per conductor and in a four-pair cable, there would be a total of eight solid wires.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Stranded cable uses multiple wires wrapped around each other in each conductor and in a four-pair with seven strands per conductor cable, there would be a total of 56 wires (2 per pair × 4 pairs × 7 strands).
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Solid core cable is intended for permanently installed runs (permanent link).
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] It is less flexible than stranded cable and is more prone to failure if repeatedly flexed due to work hardening.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Stranded cable is used at patch panels and for connections from wall ports to end devices (patch cord or drop cable), as it resists cracking of the conductors.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Connectors are designed differently for solid core than for stranded.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Use of a connector with the wrong cable type can lead to unreliable cabling.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Plugs designed for solid and stranded cores are readily available, and some vendors even offer plugs designed for use with both types.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] The punch-down blocks on patch-panel and wall-port jacks are designed for use with solid core cable.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] These work via the insulation-displacement method, whereby the device pierces the sides of the insulation and "bites" into the copper conductor to form a connection.
[src:knx-building/twisted-pair] Punchdown blocks are used as patch panels or as break-out boxes, for twisted pair cable.
